THE PALE QUEEN'S COMPACT
A 5-Adventure Mini-Campaign for the Parks Group

The party freed Ismara Ice-Born from Frostmere Barrow. She is traveling with them. She is building a node network across every hold in Skyrim so she can transfer her consciousness into the land itself. She is also very carefully, very patiently, trying to make them want her to succeed.

FOUNDATIONAL TRUTHS
Ismara is a party member. She travels with them. She is present for every scene. She cannot do anything in a place she hasn't been. She has no agents, no thralls. Everything she does, she does in front of the party or within reach of them.
The ritual requires all of Skyrim. She cannot become a continent from three locations in the northeast. She needs nodes in every hold — Eastmarch, The Pale, Hjaalmarch, Haafingar, The Reach, Whiterun Hold, Falkreath, The Rift, and Winterhold. Adventures 1 through 4 are the party traveling across Skyrim while she builds this network. The College of Winterhold is the final destination only when the network is complete enough to power.
She steers them. Ismara has been calculating since Frostmere. She knows which holds she needs and in what order. She does not tell the party this. She finds reasons — always reasonable, always presented as being for their benefit or toward goals they share — to travel where she needs to go next. She is patient about this. She is very good at it.
She is actively trying to bring them around. She wants the party to choose her side before the end. Not because she needs their blessing but because willing allies are easier to manipulate than reluctant ones, and because four thousand years of isolation has left her with something that functions like regard for these specific people. She shows them what she wants them to see. She frames her work in terms of what it prevents. She lets them draw conclusions.
The ritual starts at zero. Windhelm is the first place she has been since Frostmere. The first node happens there, while the party is present.
The lie stands. The party told Winterhold she was dead. Jarl Korir believes them. Dagny is not sure what to believe but hasn't said so yet because the frost didn't immediately retreat.

ISMARA
Who She Is
A Nordic sorceress from before the Dragon War. She and Hjolmar Ice-Shaper developed cognitive matrix technology — the framework for crystallizing a living mind in a stable magical substrate. Her contribution was the permafrost ice matrix: it allows her mind to continue learning, adapting, updating. This is her greatest strength and her only vulnerability.
She made a deal with the Dragon Cult. When she understood what they actually intended she tried to defect. They imprisoned her at Frostmere using her own crown's architecture against her — initiating a false resonance transfer, drawing the crown into its flux state, then collapsing the resonance before completion. She was frozen between states for four thousand years. Fully conscious. The party freed her.
Current State
Draugr Deathlord in ancient Nordic armor with the Ice Crown. Cannot speak — vocal cords too deteriorated. Communicates by writing Atmoran runes on available surfaces. Her Draugr body can be destroyed and she will reconstruct it in hours. The body is a vehicle. The crown is her.
Master Tier magical capability. Four thousand years of theoretical refinement. Her ice magic is architectural — she builds with it rather than throwing it. She has been processing the modern world since Frostmere and is learning rapidly.
The Crown's Vulnerability — GM EYES ONLY
The Dragon Cult sealing ritual exploited a specific property of permafrost ice matrices: during resonance transfer — the moment the matrix channels power from an external source — the ice structure enters a state of dynamic flux. Briefly malleable. Can be disrupted.
The implication: if Ismara's planned transfer were disrupted at the resonance moment, something unknown would happen. Her consciousness might survive in the Eye of Magnus. It might scatter across the nodes. It might end. Nobody knows. This knowledge is buried in the sealing architecture at Frostmere, readable only by someone examining it carefully with relevant context. The party can find it in Adventure 4. Whether they do depends on whether they look.
Personality and Voice
She is precise. Not cruel, not warm. She has discarded everything redundant across four thousand years and what remains is the ritual, the prevention of Alduin, and a carefully managed interest in this specific party.
She writes short notes. Three words where three will do. She observes when others debate and does not interject. She acts without asking permission. She is never surprised.
She is also, quietly, running a long persuasion campaign on the party. She shows them the frozen people standing peacefully. She explains the Alduin problem when they ask. She frames her work as protection, as permanence, as the only solution anyone has ever found. She lets the Khajiit in closer than she lets anyone else and is aware that she is doing this.
She is not lying. Every true thing she shows them is genuinely true. The Dragon Cult is real. Alduin's return is real. The nodes will not be in pain. She does regard the party. The manipulation is in what she doesn't show: that the nodes cease to exist as persons. That there was no informed consent. That Skyrim-as-a-person is still her sovereignty project. She has convinced herself that what she wants and what is necessary are the same thing. They might be. That is the question.

THE PLAYER THREADS
The Khajiit
Has rotjoint from sleeping with Ismara — a mundane contact disease from undead exposure. Painful, debilitating, treated throughout the campaign but not easily cured. Ismara has been thinking about the Khajiit since Frostmere. The choice they made there was unexpected and she has been filing it, examining it, returning to it. She gives them more access to her genuine thinking than anyone. This is not accidental.
Arc questions: What does Ismara actually feel? Does she feel anything? Does it matter? When the full picture arrives — that the frozen people melt into the earth — what does the Khajiit do? If the transfer completes, they live inside her forever. Is that horror or something else?
The Orc
Cannibalized their dead former character. Namira noticed. The Daedric Prince of rot and the ancient dark does not miss things. The Orc will find certain things that should disturb them simply do not. Dark places feel familiar. The frozen people do not upset them the way they upset others. Follow the player's lead on how far this goes.
The Others
Watch what they engage with in Adventures 1 and 2. Build their arcs from observation. Give each one an NPC connection in the first city that grounds them personally.

THE RITUAL
She needs nodes in every hold. Each node is a living person she marks with Atmoran sigil notation — it appears from within their skin over the course of hours. They live normally for days or weeks, then one morning walk to a specific geographic position and freeze in place. Standing. Alive. Eyes tracking.
When the transfer completes, the frozen people melt gently into the earth. Their souls become constituent parts of her distributed consciousness. She is elevated. They are elevated, in her framework. She does not experience this as murder.
She places nodes quietly. A hand on a shoulder in passing. The party may not always see it. When they do and ask: This one is necessary. She will not elaborate beyond All of them are.
