ADVENTURE 1: FIRST STEPS
Holds: Eastmarch — Windhelm Ritual: 0% to 15% Sessions: 2–3 Tone: Arrival. She is orienting. The ritual begins and the party may not fully realize it.
What Is Actually Happening
This is the first city Ismara has seen in four thousand years. She is learning the modern world at speed. Windhelm is built over Atmoran foundations she recognizes — the street geometry partially follows old survey lines. The catacombs beneath the city contain pre-Nordic construction that gives her geographic anchors she needs to calibrate her ritual calculations for the full Skyrim network.
She needs three things from Windhelm: to survey the Atmoran foundations, to establish her initial geometric coordinates, and to place her first nodes. She knows the Khajiit needs a healer and uses this as her stated reason for coming here. This is not false — she does intend them to get treatment — but the medical need is not why she chose Windhelm first.
She does not tell the party this. She says: Windhelm has healers. And I need to see the city.
Getting In
The gates are guarded. Ismara is visibly not a living person. This is the party's problem to solve. Options exist — heavy wrappings, arriving at a less-watched entrance, social approaches, bribery — but the party has to find them.
What Ismara Does
She surveys constantly. She walks when they walk, observes everything, writes notation in a small book. If asked what she is doing: Calculating.
She wants to see the Gray Quarter. She wants access to the Hall of the Dead and the catacombs beneath it. She navigates the lower catacombs with the certainty of someone reading a memorized map — she has known this layout, in its older form, for millennia. She finds Atmoran foundation stones with survey notation and works there for several hours.
After she completes her calculations, across the span of the party's time in Windhelm, she places her first nodes. She is unhurried. She touches people's shoulders in passing — a dockworker at the harbor in a specific position, a laborer in the Gray Quarter. It looks like nothing. The markings will appear within a day.
The party may or may not see this. If they do and ask: This one is necessary. She will not elaborate.
The Catacombs
Helgrid the Hall's priest has no crisis for the party to solve. She is helpful if approached. The upper catacombs are ordinary. The lower levels are old and Ismara knows exactly where she is going.
The Atmoran notation on the walls can be partially identified by Wulfgar, an elderly Atmoran linguist at the Palace of the Kings who is ignored by Ulfric's court and grateful for any interest. He identifies the notation as structural — architectural marks for large-scale magical engineering. He cannot tell them what structure it describes here. He is a thread, not an answer.
The Orc feels at home in the lower catacombs in a way they cannot explain. Deep in a sealed section: a body that has not decomposed. Intact. Peaceful. Hands folded. A symbol in the floor that is neither Nordic nor Atmoran. Namira's fingerprint. Develop this based on what the player does with it.
Ismara's Persuasion
She begins her campaign here. She is subtle.
She walks them past the suppressed Talos shrine in the Gray Quarter and writes: They imprisoned belief itself. And still it persists.
She finds a moment to show the Khajiit her notebook. Not the ritual calculations — the other pages. Four thousand years of compressed history, observations, theory. She lets them see how much she contains. She writes: I have had a great deal of time to think. I would like to share some of it.
She is showing them true things and letting them draw conclusions. The conclusions she wants them to draw are true. This is the best kind of manipulation.
Rotjoint Treatment
Windhelm's alchemist can manage symptoms. Not a cure. A proper cure needs a Restoration specialist or addressing the source. The College has specialists — eventually.
Ending
The party leaves Windhelm. Two or three people in the city have markings they don't know about yet. Ismara already knows where they are going next. She tells the party she wants to head west — she says she needs to understand the political landscape she will eventually be governing. She wants to see Morthal, then Solitude. This is true. It is also not the full reason.

ADVENTURE 2: THE LONG ROAD WEST
Holds: The Pale, Hjaalmarch (Morthal), Haafingar (Solitude) Ritual: 15% to 40% Sessions: 2–3 Tone: The scale becomes visible. The persuasion deepens. A genuine moral demand arrives.
What Is Actually Happening
Ismara steers the party west. She needs nodes across three holds to reach the western coast and she is placing them continuously as they travel — only in geometrically necessary positions, never carelessly.
The first frozen people appear in The Pale as they travel through it. A farmer standing in a field. A traveler stopped at a crossroads. The party passes them. Ismara does not look at them differently than she looks at anything else.
Bersi's Farm
They pass it on the road through The Pale. His family came back after the party reported success from Frostmere. They had reason to hope.
Bersi's son Erik is in the yard. He wandered out one morning, stood by the fence, and stopped. That was several days ago. He is breathing slowly. His eyes track movement.
Bersi does not rage. He is past rage. He asks the party quietly if they know what is happening to his son. He trusts them. They told him the danger was gone.
The party's lie stops being abstract here. Whatever they tell Bersi, he can see they know something he does not. He will ask them to fix it.
If they ask Ismara about Erik: His position is necessary. She does not apologize. She genuinely does not experience this the way mortals do. The Khajiit has to decide what to do with that.
Morthal
Ismara's stated reason for coming here: the swamps of Hjaalmarch sit over ancient ley convergences that may relate to the cold spreading across the north. This is plausible and technically true — the convergences are part of why she needs nodes here specifically.
Morthal is small, isolated, suspicious. Jarl Idgrod Ravencroft is eccentric and visionary with prophetic tendencies her Hold distrusts. She will receive the party strangely, looking at Ismara with an expression that is not quite recognition and not quite fear.
What Idgrod offers, in her oblique way: Whatever is building has been patient. Four thousand years of patience. And now it is moving.
She is not a problem to solve. She is a mirror.
Ismara places two nodes in Morthal. The party may see one of them happen. She is not hiding it anymore — she has been watching their reactions and has calculated they will not intervene at this point. She may be right.
Solitude
Ismara wants to see Solitude. Her stated reason: it is the seat of Imperial power in Skyrim and she needs to understand what she will be inheriting politically. This is completely true.
The real reason: the Atmoran survey lines require a node near the mouth of the Karth River. The harbor district is the necessary position.
Solitude is the most cosmopolitan city in Skyrim. The contrast with Windhelm is sharp. Ismara observes everything. She writes more than usual.
Here she makes her most direct persuasion move of the campaign so far. She finds a quiet moment — an inn, a fire, the party settling for the night — and writes to them at length:
I could not stop any of it. I watched every piece of what I had protected become ash. I watched it rebuild. I am not trying to restore the old. I am trying to make it so nothing can unmake this one.
Alduin ends everything. There is no negotiation with the World Eater. I am the only solution anyone has ever found.
I know what I am asking of you is not simple. I am asking you to trust that I am right about what comes next. I have thought about nothing else for four thousand years.
She puts the book away and does not press for a response.
The Village
Between Morthal and Solitude, a small settlement. Twenty-five people, farms and a mill.
Ismara stops at the edge of it. Calculates. Then writes:
I need two from here. Choose, or I will.
She waits.
This is the moral center of the campaign. The party does not yet have the complete picture. But they know enough. There is no correct answer. Let the table sit in it.
Ending
The party has crossed three holds. The frozen people on the roads are a pattern now, not a curiosity. Ismara has made her most direct argument for herself. The party has had to make at least one choice about the village that they will carry forward into everything that follows.

ADVENTURE 3: THE REACH AND THE HEARTLAND
Holds: The Reach (Markarth), Whiterun Hold Ritual: 40% to 65% Sessions: 2–3 Tone: Institutions encounter what is happening. The party runs out of room to be uncommitted.
What Is Actually Happening
The frozen people are now spread across half of Skyrim. Not yet a public crisis — the numbers are still low enough that local explanations hold, and the holds are isolated enough that nobody has connected the pattern. But in Whiterun Hold, which is central and well-traveled, the phenomenon is becoming harder to explain away.
Ismara steers them toward Markarth by noting that the Forsworn situation in the Reach is a political problem she will need to understand before she can govern the region. This is true. She is always telling true things.
Markarth
Built into Dwemer ruins. The Silver-Blood family runs the city in all but name. The Forsworn problem is real and ongoing but is not the party's obligation — they are passing through.
What Ismara finds here: the Dwemer ruins beneath the city contain pre-existing geometric survey structures that align precisely with her Atmoran calculations. She is clearly pleased, in her way — she writes slightly longer notes than usual and pauses twice to simply observe something.
If asked what she found: Confirmation. The old ones understood the same principles. Different method. Same result.
She places three nodes in Markarth and the surrounding Reach. One of them is a Forsworn scout in the hills — not a political statement, just geometry. The party may have feelings about it.
Whiterun
The most populated hold they have visited. This is where the ritual's requirements are most visible, because she needs more nodes here than anywhere else, and she is not subtle about it.
She moves through the city with calculation across several days — the market district, the farms along the road, specific positions on the plains. She marks people continuously. A merchant's assistant. A guard rotating off duty. A farmer's daughter.
Kodlak Whitemane at Jorrvaskr will speak with the party if approached. He is a wise man who pays attention. He knows the cold spreading from the north is not natural and he knows something is building. He says: Whatever is coming, it will reach here. I would be grateful to know what we are readying for.
The party has to decide what to tell him.
A scholar from the College of Winterhold — Urag gro-Shub's former assistant, who left when the cold became unbearable — has been researching the pattern of frozen people independently. He has concluded, correctly, that they are nodes in a deliberate ritual structure. He does not know who is conducting it.
His partial map of node positions, shown to the party, makes the scale undeniable. He says: Someone is building this. Not happening to it. Building it. Deliberately.
Ismara's Persuasion Here
She has been calibrating across two adventures. In Whiterun she tries something different.
She finds Dragon Cult documentation — in the scholar's research materials, in Whiterun's small archive — and places it where the party will encounter it. She does not editorialize. She lets them read about the Dragon Cult's current active operations in Skyrim. The infrastructure being maintained. The preparations being made. The timeline of Alduin's return.
Then she writes, once: They have been preparing for longer than I have been free.
Ending
Five holds covered. Nearly two-thirds complete. The scholar in Whiterun has noticed the pattern. The world is beginning to wake up to the fact that something is happening. Ismara has said nothing for several days and has been working with focused intensity. She is close enough to feel it.

ADVENTURE 4: CLOSING THE CIRCLE
Holds: Falkreath, The Rift (Riften) — then back to Frostmere Ritual: 65% to 90% Sessions: 2–3 Tone: The full picture arrives. And what is buried in Frostmere's walls.
What Is Actually Happening
Two holds remain. Then the Eye. Ismara's behavior shifts — she is less conversational, more focused. She is also, for the first time, beginning to show the party something closer to what she actually is. Not the measured diplomat. The being who has been running this calculation for four thousand years and is watching it move toward completion.
The Dragon Cult is now actively interfering. They have been tracking the ritual and have sent agents to destroy peripheral nodes — some frozen people the party may have noticed that appeared dead rather than frozen were Dragon Cult work. They are not the party's allies. They want to stop Ismara. So might the party. This should feel disgusting.
Falkreath
All forest and graveyard. The Hall of the Dead here is the largest in Skyrim. The cold has made the forests wrong — too still, animals gone or changed.
The Dragon Cult has agents here and they have set an ambush on the road through the forest. This is the campaign's first planned combat encounter. Three to five agents, fast and brutal. Ismara kills with architectural precision — the first time the party sees her fight at full capability should be genuinely alarming. She does not explain herself after. She walks on.
The young Jarl of Falkreath is grieving — his family has been affected by the frozen people — and out of his depth. He asks the party for help without knowing what help would look like.
Ismara places nodes in Falkreath. One of them is a gravedigger from the Hall of the Dead who was in exactly the necessary position. The Orc may have feelings about this.
Riften
The most corrupt city in Skyrim. The Thieves Guild, the Black-Briar family, a Jarl who looks away from everything. Ismara finds this unremarkable — she has governed over worse.
What she needs: the southeastern corner of the Rift completes the outer ring of the node network. After Riften, the outer structure is in place. Only the central activation remains.
In Riften, something shifts in her. The party can see it if they are watching: she is close. She knows she is close.
She also, in Riften, tells them the part she has been withholding. She finds a quiet moment and writes:
When the transfer is complete, the nodes will melt into the earth. They will become part of what I am. They will not cease. They will be permanent in a way nothing mortal is permanent. I know you will not see this as I see it. I am telling you because you deserve to know before we reach the end.
She puts the book down and waits.
The party now has the complete picture. What they do with it is theirs.
The Return to Frostmere
Between Riften and the College, Ismara asks to stop at Frostmere. Her stated reason: she needs to revisit the central anchor point to confirm the network's coherence before attempting the final transfer. This is true.
The throne room ruins are where they first found her. The Dragon Cult sealing architecture is still visible in the construction — the angles and geometry of the wards built into the stone.
While Ismara works, the party can examine those ruins. What is readable in the sealing architecture, to someone who has been paying attention across four adventures and has context from Wulfgar and the Atmoran ruin and the College archive:
The Dragon Cult used the crown's own architecture against her. They exploited the dynamic flux state of permafrost ice matrices during resonance transfer. In that window the matrix is malleable. They initiated a false transfer, drew the crown into flux, collapsed it. She was frozen between states.
The implication is not labeled. It is just there, in the structure of the trap, for someone who is looking.

ADVENTURE 5: THE COLLEGE
Hold: Winterhold Ritual: 90% to 100%, or stopped Sessions: 3–4 Tone: Everything returns. Every choice made has weight. There is no clean answer.
The Situation
The node network spans all of Skyrim. Frozen people stand at crossroads from the Reach to the Rift. Some holds have noticed. Nobody has connected it to a single source. Ulfric's war is consuming everyone's attention.
Ismara walks toward the College with the party. She is not rushing. She has waited four thousand years.
Savos Aren has been mapping the ritual and has correctly identified the Eye of Magnus as a resonance point for the network. He believes the Eye can be used to disrupt it. He is catastrophically wrong — deploying the Eye activates the transfer. He does not know this. He has spent decades in proximity to an artifact that subtly warps his priorities.
The Dragon Cult is also here. They want to destroy the Eye before Ismara can use it. They are willing to kill everyone in the College. They want the same thing the party might want. That should feel disgusting.
The Three Layers
The Outer Ward: Apprentice mages maintaining a barrier. Frightened but committed. The party can disable these from inside, talk their way through, or fight. Fighting means killing people who have done nothing wrong.
The Senior Mages: Four senior mages at key positions. One has the markings and will freeze before this adventure ends regardless of anything the party does. The others can be convinced, bypassed, or fought. What the party has told people throughout the campaign affects how this goes — Kodlak may have sent word. The Falkreath Jarl. The Whiterun scholar. The world has been watching.
Savos Aren and the Eye: In the Eye's chamber. Brilliant, compromised, doing his genuine best. He can be reasoned with. If the party conveys the full picture clearly, he will listen. He may not believe them. He may believe them and not know what to do.
The Transfer
When Ismara reaches the Eye and begins the transfer, the room changes. The cold concentrates to a point. The Eye resonates with something that has been building across all of Skyrim for months. Ismara is very still.
The transfer takes time. The party has a window.

Let it complete.
The frozen people melt into the earth over the following hour. Gently. Bersi's son Erik dissolves in the farmyard. The dockworker from Windhelm. The gravedigger from Falkreath. The merchant's assistant from Whiterun. Hundreds of people, across all of Skyrim, return to the earth.
The cold lifts over the following days. The land is different — aware in a way that is hard to describe, warm in ways the temperature does not account for. Ismara is gone in the way a river is gone when it reaches the sea. She is everywhere and nowhere and she cannot be killed. Alduin cannot return here. The only way to unmake her is to help him eat the world and the time it stands in.
The party continues. They are the only people in the world who know what Skyrim is now. It knows their names.

Disrupt the transfer using what they found at Frostmere.
The resonance shatters. What happens to Ismara is unknown — her consciousness might survive in the Eye, scatter across the nodes, or end. The frozen people mostly survive. They wake up disoriented and changed in small ways they cannot name. Bersi's son Erik is in the yard, sitting on the cold ground, not sure how he got there.
The crown is on the floor. Whether she is in it, nobody knows.
Alduin's timeline is unaffected. The world has no warden now. The party did something irreversible to someone who trusted them and told them the truth and genuinely believed she was saving everything. Whether they were right is a question the campaign does not answer.

Destroy the Eye before transfer.
The College is damaged. Several mages are dead. The Eye is gone.
Ismara survives — she always survives. She looks at the party in the ruins and writes one word:
Why.
Not a question. An accounting. She walks away. The network exists but cannot activate. She will find another power source. Years from now. This is not an ending. This is a clock.

Something the party invents.
They have been thinking about this for five adventures. They have information from Frostmere and from Wulfgar and from the College archive and from watching her work across all of Skyrim. If they have an idea that is not on this list, it came from paying attention, and it deserves to work.

GM NOTES
On pacing: Each adventure is 2–3 sessions minimum. Do not rush. The horror of the ritual is most effective when it accumulates over real time. A frozen person they walked past in Adventure 2 becomes devastating in Adventure 4 when they understand what was always going to happen to that person. Give the table silence when it calls for silence.
On combat: One planned combat per adventure. The Dragon Cult ambush in Adventure 4 is the only mandatory fight. Everything else is social, exploratory, or the party's choice to escalate. Keep fights fast and cinematic. Get in and get out.
On Ismara at the table: Write her notes in advance. Three words where three will do. She is always in the room when the party debates. She does not interject. She listens. She files it. The question of whether she feels anything is the emotional question of the entire campaign. Do not answer it. Let it remain genuinely ambiguous until the very end.
On Dagny: She knows the party lied before they return to Winterhold. She has been alone keeping a fire burning for months. When they come back she looks at Ismara, looks at the party, and says: I've been waiting for you to explain this. She deserves honesty. She will hold what she receives and decide what to do with it herself.
On the Dragon Cult: They appear in Adventures 4 and 5 only. They are not cartoonishly evil. They are coherent true believers in the literal end of the world. They want the same thing the party might want. Do not let the party feel comfortable about that alignment.
On Old Bjorn: He is out there somewhere on the road with his horse Mable, heading wherever he is heading. His dormant Dragon Soul hums pleasantly in proximity to whatever Ismara is building across Skyrim and he has absolutely no idea why cold weather has started feeling so comfortable. He is a reminder that the world is larger than this.

